      • addRandomSpawn

        public static boolean addRandomSpawn(EntityNMS12.SpawnData data,
                                     EntityNMS12.MobMeta meta,
                                     EntityNMS12.Biome... biomes)
        Makes the mob spawn randomly around the world just like vanilla mobs.

        Unlike the other method, this allows you to choose the 'category' of your mob; Creature, Monster, Ambient or Water Creature - even if it in reality was none of those.

        If you're using a custom entity class, remember to register it before using this! Otherwise it'll not be rendered by the client.

        If #isAccessible() returns false, the process will not be executed.

        Parameters:
        data - - The spawn data (chance, amount, spawn weight..)
        meta - - The category in which your mob'll spawn (i.e creatures'll spawn in day, monsters during night..)
        biomes - - The array of biomes to let the mobs spawn in, use EntityNMS12.Biome.COLLECTION_ALL for all of them.
        See Also:
        #registerEntity(MobType, Class, boolean)

      • addRandomSpawn

        public static boolean addRandomSpawn(EntityNMS12.Type type,
                                     EntityNMS12.SpawnData data,
                                     EntityNMS12.Biome... biomes)
        Adds a random spawn for the mob with the specified arguments.

        If you're using a custom entity class, remember to register it before using this! Otherwise it'll not be rendered by the client.

        If #isAccessible() returns false, the process will not be executed.

        Parameters:
        type - - The mob type to spawn
        data - - The spawn data (chance, amount, spawn weight..)
        biomes - - The array of biomes to let the mobs spawn in, use EntityNMS12.Biome.COLLECTION_ALL for all of them.
        See Also:
        #registerEntity(MobType, Class, boolean), addRandomSpawn(SpawnData, MobMeta, Biome...)

      • registerWithoutID

        public static void registerWithoutID(String name,
                                     Class<? extends net.minecraft.server.v1_12_R1.Entity> clazz)
        Registers your entity without an internal id like most of the mobs have. Not sure where you'd need this but here you go.

        Can still be spawned via /summon.

        Note: Since no mob Type can be provided, overriding default mobs is not possible.

        Parameters:
        name - - The 'savegame id' of your mob (ex. "custom_zombie")
        clazz - - The class of your custom entity

      • registerEntity

        public static void registerEntity(EntityNMS12.Type type,
                                  Class<? extends net.minecraft.server.v1_12_R1.Entity> customClass,
                                  boolean override)
        Registers the custom class to be available for use.
        Parameters:
        type - - The type of your mob
        customClass - - Your custom class that'll be used
        override - - Should your mob be set as a default in each biome? Only one custom entity of this type entity can have this set as 'true'.

      • registerEntity

        public static void registerEntity(String name,
                                  EntityNMS12.Type type,
                                  Class<? extends net.minecraft.server.v1_12_R1.Entity> customClass,
                                  EntityNMS12.Biome... biomes)
        Registers the custom class to be available for use.
        Parameters:
        id - - The mob id. BE CAREFUL with this. Your Minecraft client renders the entity based on this, and if used improperly, will cause unexpected behavior!
        name - - The 'savegame id' of the mob.
        type - - The type of your mob
        customClass - - Your custom class that'll be used
        biomes - - The array of biomes to make the mob spawn in.
        See Also:
        #registerEntity(int, String, MobType, Class, Biome[]), EntityType#getName() for the savegame id., EntityType#getId() for the correct mob id.
